  • 【Personalized Smart Watches for Women】As the latest women's smart watch in 2025, we have equipped it with 2 watch bands to choose from - the metal band is elegant and suitable for any daily occasion, and silicone bands are casual and suitable for matching sportswear.In addition, there are more than 160 watch face styles are optional, and you can also upload photos according to your own preferences for personal customization.
  • 【Bluetooth Connection for Calls/ Messages】With Bluetooth connection, you can easily make and answer calls directly on your smart watch without taking out your phone. It will also alert you when there are text messages or notifications from social media like Facebook, WhatsApp and Twitter. Even if your phone is in your bag, you won't miss any important calls and messages. Note that you can't edit or reply to messages from your smartwatch.
  • 【Heart Rate & Sleep Monitoring】The smart watch for women uses an advanced sensor chip and a photoelectric sensor for accurate monitoring. It provides 24-hour continuous measurement of your health indicators (heart rate, and stress), as well as women's menstrual cycle reminders. In addition, the ladies smart watch automatically monitors your sleep status (deep sleep, light sleep, waking up) and provides a comprehensive sleep quality analysis, so better sleep starts now.
  • 【100+ SPORTS MODES AND IP67 WATERPROOF】This running watch has 100+ sports modes such as walking, running, dancing, fighting, equipment-based exercises, ball games, swimming, leisure, etc. Allowing you to intuitively read comprehensive sports data (steps, calories, heart rate, etc.). At the same time, this women's watch has also passed the IP67 waterproof test, which can prevent damage from rain and sweat, helping you with worry-free monitoring of exercise conditions in different environments.
  • 【More Practical Gadgets & Built-in Speaker】 It serves more practical functions, such as alarm, stopwatch, timer, find phones, brightness adjustment and weather display, breath training, breath rate, raising hand to activate display, remote camera, find device, sedentary alert. The built-in speaker allows you to play music and answer calls through the watch.

      I’ve been wearing this for a day and I’m obsessed.       Features I like:
      - You can change the watch face; there are fun designs. I keep it digital because it’s easier to read than analog :)
      - You swipe left to access different screens like Activity, Blood Pressure, Heart Rate, Weather and you can customize these on the last “Favorites” screen
      - You can take pictures on your phone remotely from your watch by clicking the Shutter
      - You can pair to your phone to control music whether you’re listening on your watch or AirPods
      - There’s a feature to find your phone from your watch
      - You can put it on Low Power Mode so the watch face won’t activate/light up at night while you’re sleeping

      These features probably aren’t new to anyone who has had an Apple Watch, but I never have so I’m geeking out over these cool features.

      I haven’t figured out a way to sync my steps from my watch with my phone but I plan to always be wearing my watch so it’s not a big deal.

      The watch is very pretty with an easily adjustable band which I appreciated since I have a small wrist. It's designed to look dressy but still looks great for casual days.

      CONS: The heart rate, stress level, O2 level and sleep functions worked well but the blood pressure and steps were completely inaccurate. What I didn't like about the step counting is that it takes a while for the steps to be counted; troubleshooting said you have to walk around approximately 12 steps for it to start counting after the watch has been in "sleep mode" - I have several smart watches and none of them hesitate with counting steps. Once it did start counting I had no way of knowing if it was accurate or not. Another thing I didn't like was there were no detailed instructions to help you along if you're unfamiliar with a smart watch and troubleshooting tips were in broken English. I also did not see any way to contact them if you had a problem (I may have overlooked contact info but I did look thoroughly). There were watch faces to choose from and they loaded quickly but I did have the watch face change all on its own 2 times.

      PROS: It did pair easily and quickly and stayed connected with no problem, the other features worked well, it's comfortable and looks great. I really wanted to love it but I returned it.

    • CandidNikki
      4.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
      Not bad, a good value for the low price point
      Reviewed in the United States on January 13, 2025
      Style: G02-Rose gold
      I tried 3 smartwatches in this price range capable of checking and tracking blood pressure and heart rate. I know smartwatches aren’t meant to be relied on like actual hospital equipment, and I know this technology has a long way to go, but I was diagnosed with POTS and... See more
      I tried 3 smartwatches in this price range capable of checking and tracking blood pressure and heart rate. I know smartwatches aren’t meant to be relied on like actual hospital equipment, and I know this technology has a long way to go, but I was diagnosed with POTS and needed a way to check what’s going on with my body quickly when I have a syncopal episode. By the time I could get to my doctor’s office, the episodes have passed. This watch is the one I decided to keep because it is the only one that successfully sends its data to my Apple Health app. The other two did not, or only sent partial information (not the BP or HR which are most important for me).

      In case anyone has needs similar to mine, here are my notes on this watch:

      Pros:
      -The watch does successfully sync and send data to my Apple Health app.
      -BP readings are pretty close to accurate, my testing against my Omron cuff only had the watch 1-2 numbers higher than the cuff. The other watches I tested were approximately 5 numbers higher than the cuff. No one will be making crucial diagnostic decisions based on the watch readings, but having the tracking history is helpful. This suits my needs.
      -The size of the watch face is more manageable for me. I would prefer the bigger, Apple Watch style square screen, but that was just too bulky for my wrist and comfort.
      -The screen quality is better than the other 2 watches I tested. The picture is sharper and colors are more vibrant, plus the tactile response time and overall performance is faster than those other watches.
      -Taking vital sign readings, downloading a new watch face, and pretty much all functions are much quicker with this watch compared to the others. I’m guessing there is a faster processor in this one.
      -The watch recharges quickly. But see the Cons below for my thoughts on the charger itself.
      -The UI/UX is pretty easily managed. If you’re used to using a smartphone, using this watch should be pretty intuitive once you can remember which directional swipe does what.

      Cons:
      -Battery life. With one of the other watches I tested, I could have gone a week without having to charge. This one needs to be charged daily.
      -No matter how much I tried, I couldn’t get my SMS messaging to sync to the watch. WhatsApp messages come through, but the Messages app from my iPhone has been unable to notify me via the watch.
      -Not many good watch faces to choose from in the DaFit app. There are a decent number of options (although the GloryFit app had much more) but most of the options are kind of juvenile or just not to my taste. This surprised me because I’m not that picky.
      -Like many of the watches in this price range, you need the DaFit app to pair and use the watch. DaFit has a bit of a language deficit, the English is sometimes hard to decipher because the intended meaning is sometimes lost in translation. I’m usually able to figure out what they meant, but not always. It’s should be noted that this issue is also present on the GloryFit app many other watches use.
      -The instructions that come with the watch don’t explain how to resize the mesh band or change the bands. I was able to figure it out from good old YouTube, but it would have been nice if the manual would have explained that so I didn’t have to go hunting for the information. (If you’re reading this and need to know how to resize it, use the included tool to pop open the clasp via the open notch)
      -The watch face somehow changes itself on its own about once a week. I haven’t figured out yet why this is happening.
      -Even when I’ve turned off the ability for the watch to ring or act as a speaker, it sometimes does for incoming calls. It also randomly will take over the sound, and the audio for whatever I’m watching or listening to on my phone comes through the watch instead of my phone. I haven’t figured out yet why that can happen even when I’ve got the settings set to not do that.
      -The connector on the charging cable is awful. It seems like the same charger is used for all watches in this price range. It’s meant to magnetically latch on to the watch to maintain contact while charging, but the strength of the magnet is pitiful. The charging cable comes away from the watch with barely a whisper. Every single time I go to charge the watch (which is daily, unfortunately, because it seems like battery life is poor on this model) the charger slips or falls off at least twice between my connecting it and trying to set the watch down on my night stand to charge. This is actually the only Con from this list that actually annoys me regularly. The rest of the Cons I can live with easily.
